Today is April 28. Barbados is approximately August 1. That's 14 weeks. Here's how the time spends.
I'm going to lay this out as a sequence of phases, with what gets done in each, who owns what, and what gets cut if a phase runs long.
The three workstreams
Before the phases, here are the workstreams:
Workstream 1 — Engineering. The platform itself. The financial spine. Module migrations. RLS hardening. Tournament logic. Audience features. Sponsor metrics. Owner: you, with v0 doing implementation under tight prompts.
Workstream 2 — Brand & Experience. Visual design, copy voice, cultural calibration for Barbados, the spectator experience, the player check-in flow, the moments-of-delight. Owner: you, with input from the Barbados team. May involve a designer or content person if budget permits.
Workstream 3 — Go-to-Market. Audience acquisition for Barbados attendees, sponsor outreach, partnership conversations, the public-facing event marketing. Primary owner: the Barbados team. Your role: provide them with platform tools (event landing pages, share-friendly URLs, sponsor mockups), unblock their work.
These three run in parallel. The engineering workstream has the heaviest weight and tightest constraints. The other two ramp up over time.
