Abort conditions
These are the conditions under which you stop and have a hard conversation with Barbados:

Phase 3 (foundation work) takes 8+ weeks instead of 4. This means the architecture rewrite is fundamentally harder than estimated. At week 8 of Phase 3 (so by mid-July), if T-005 and T-011 aren't done, you have to evaluate whether August is feasible.
A second audit (planned for end of Phase 3) reveals critical bugs of comparable severity to the first. The first audit found 10 critical bugs. If a second audit on the post-rewrite code finds 5+ more critical bugs, the architecture is still fragile and shipping it for real money is irresponsible.
The Barbados team's audience acquisition motion is not generating pre-registration interest by end of June. If 0 pre-registrations exist 6 weeks before the event, the event itself may not work, regardless of platform readiness.
A critical workstream loses its owner. If you can't sustain the engineering workload AND the brand workstream AND the relationship with Barbados, you have to either bring in help or descope.

For each abort condition, the action is: have a direct conversation with the Barbados team about timeline. Not "we cancel" — "we deliver a smaller version, or we move the date by 2-4 weeks, or we run a smaller pilot." Bootstrapping companies have flexibility that VC-backed companies don't. Use it.
